'''Jackie Chan''' [[Silver Bauhinia Star|SBS]], (born [[April 7]], [[1954]] in [[Victoria Peak]], [[Hong Kong]]), also known as '''Sing Lung''' ({{zh-stp|s=成龙|t=成龍|p=Chéng Lóng}}), born '''Chan Kong Sang''' ({{zh-stp|s=陈港生|t=陳港生|p=Chén Gǎngshēng}}), is a [[China|Chinese]] [[actor]], [[Film director|director]], [[martial artist]], [[film producer]], [[screenwriter]], [[singer]] and [[stunt]] performer.

Chan is one of the best-known names in [[kung fu]] and [[action movie]]s worldwide for his [[acrobatics|acrobatic]] [[fighting style]], comic timing, use of [[improvised weapons]] and innovative stunts. He has appeared in over 100 [[film]]s and has received stars on the [[Avenue of Stars, Hong Kong|Hong Kong Avenue of Stars]] and the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. He is also a [[Cantopop]] star, having released 20 albums since 1984 and having sung many of the [[Theme music|theme songs]] for the films in which he has starred.

==Childhood and beginnings==
[[Image:Jackie Chan Fist.JPG|thumb|left|Jackie Chan began his film career as a stuntman in the 1971 Bruce Lee film ''[[Fist of Fury]]''.]]
Jackie Chan was born in 1954 on [[Victoria Peak]], [[Hong Kong]], as Chan Kong Sang (meaning "born in Hong Kong") to [[Charles and Lee-Lee Chan]], refugees from the [[Chinese Civil War]]. He was nicknamed ''Pao Pao'' ({{zh-c|c=炮炮}}, literally meaning "Cannonball") because he was always rolling around as an infant.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Biography of Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = Hong Kong Film.net
  | date =
  | url = http://www.hkfilm.net/chanbio.htm
  | format = 
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> Since his parents worked for the French [[Ambassador (diplomacy)|ambassador]] to Hong Kong, Chan spent his formative years within the grounds of the ambassador's residence on Victoria Peak.<ref name=Tiscali>{{cite web
  | title = Biography of Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = Tiscali
  | date =
  | url = http://www.tiscali.co.uk/entertainment/film/biographies/jackie_chan_biog.html
  | format = 
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}
</ref> They emigrated to [[Canberra]], [[Australia]] in 1960, with Chan attending Nah-Hwa Primary School, where he twice failed to pass the first grade. As a result, his father sent him back to Hong Kong to enrol at the China Drama Academy, a [[Peking Opera School]] run by Master [[Yu Jim Yuen]].<ref name=Tiscali/> 

Chan trained rigorously for the next decade, excelling in martial arts and acrobatics.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Biography of Jackie Chan
  | work =
  | publisher = StarPulse
  | date = 
  | url = http://www.starpulse.com/Actors/Chan,_Jackie/Biography/
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> He eventually joined the [[Seven Little Fortunes]], a performance group made up of the school's best students, gaining the stage name Yuen Lo in homage to his master. Chan became close friends with fellow group members [[Sammo Hung]] and [[Yuen Biao]], the three of them later to be known as the ''Three Brothers'' or ''Three Dragons''.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Seven Little Fortunes
  | work = Feature article
  | publisher = LoveAsianFilm
  | date =
  | url = http://www.loveasianfilm.com/features/sevenlittlefortunes.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

Chan began his career in the film industry at the age of 17, as a stuntman in the [[1971 in film|1971]] [[Bruce Lee]] film ''[[Fist of Fury]]'' under the stage name Chen Yuen Long.<ref name="AskMen">{{cite web
  | title = Men of the Week: Entertainment, Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography 
  | publisher = AskMen
  | date = 
  | url = http://uk.askmen.com/men/entertainment/54c_jackie_chan.html
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> He received his first starring role later that year, in ''[[Little Tiger of Canton]]'', which had a limited release in Hong Kong in 1973.<ref name="Bioch">{{cite web
  | title = Real Lives: Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = The Biography Channel
  | url = http://www.thebiographychannel.co.uk/biography_story/861:1217/1/Jackie_Chan.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref>

Chan moved back to Canberra in 1976, where he briefly attended [[Dickson College]] and worked as a construction worker.<ref>{{cite news 
  | last = Boogs
  | first = Monika
  | title = Jackie Chan's tears for 'greatest' mother
  | work = 
  | pages =
  | language =
  | publisher = The Canberra Times
  | date = [[2002-03-07]]
  | url = http://canberra.yourguide.com.au/detail.asp?class=news&subclass=local&story_id=132756&category=general%20news&m=3&y=2002
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> A fellow builder named Jack took Chan under his wing, earning Chan the nickname of "Little Jack" which was later shortened to "Jackie".<ref name="Iamjc">{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan - Actor and Stuntman
  | work =
  | publisher = BBC
  | date = [[2001-07-24]]
  | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/dna/h2g2/A592760
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-06 }}</ref> In addition, Chan's [[Chinese name]] was changed to Fong Si Lung, as his father's original surname was Fong.<ref name="Iamjc" />

==Film career==
[[Image:DrunkenMaster DVDcover.jpg|thumb|right|The 1978 film ''[[Drunken Master]]'' brought Jackie Chan into the mainstream.]]
===Early exploits: 1976-1980===
Jackie Chan returned to Hong Kong in 1976 and teamed up with film director [[Lo Wei]], who planned to model him after [[Bruce Lee]] in the film ''[[New Fist of Fury]]''. His stage name was changed to Sing Lung (Chinese: 成龍, literally "become the dragon") to emphasise his similarity to Bruce Lee, whose Chinese stage name was Lei Siu Lung (Chinese: 李小龍, meaning "Little Dragon"). However, the film was unsuccessful because Chan was not accustomed to Lee's martial arts style. Despite the film's failure, Lo Wei insisted on producing films with similar themes, resulting in little improvement at the box office.<ref name="FightingMaster">{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan, a martial arts success story
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = Fighting Master
  | date =
  | url = http://www.fightingmaster.com/actors/jackie/index.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

Chan's first major breakthrough was the 1978 film ''[[Snake in the Eagle's Shadow]]'', shot while he was loaned to [[Seasonal Films]] under a two-picture deal.<ref>{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = Ng Kwong Loong (JackieChanMovie.com)
  | date =
  | url = http://www.jackiechanmovie.com/profile/biography/bio.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-07-09 }}</ref> Director [[Yuen Woo Ping]] granted Chan complete control over his own techniques, which resulted in the establishment of a new comedic kung fu genre. The shooting had its dangers; one of Chan's teeth was accidentally kicked out by fellow actor [[Hwang Jang Lee]] during filming. When released, the film proved to be a breath of fresh air for the Hong Kong audience.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Pollard
  | first = Mark
  | title = Snake in the Eagle's Shadow
  | work = Movie review
  | publisher = Kung Fu Cinema
  | date =
  | url = http://www.kungfucinema.com/reviews/snakeintheeaglesshadow.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref> Chan then starred in ''[[Drunken Master]]'', which finally propelled him to mainstream success.<ref>{{cite web
  | last = Pollard
  | first = Mark
  | title = Drunken Master
  | work = Movie review
  | publisher = Kung Fu Cinema
  | date =
  | url = http://www.kungfucinema.com/reviews/drunkenmaster.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

Upon Chan's return to Lo Wei's studio, Lo tried to replicate the comedic approach of ''Drunken Master'', producing ''[[Half a Loaf of Kung Fu]]'' and ''[[Spiritual Kung Fu]]''.<ref name="Iamjc" /> He also gave Chan the opportunity to co-direct ''[[Fearless Hyena]]'' with [[Kenneth Tsang]]. During the shooting of [[Fearless Hyena Part II|its sequel]], Chan broke his contract and joined [[Golden Harvest]], prompting Lo Wei to use his [[Triad society|triad]] connections to blackmail Chan. The dispute was resolved with the help of fellow actor and director [[Jimmy Wang Yu]], allowing Chan to stay with Golden Harvest.<ref name="Jcm">{{cite web
  | title = Jackie Chan profile
  | work = Biography
  | publisher = JackieChanMovie.com
  | date =
  | url = http://www.jackiechanmovie.com/profile/biography/bio.htm
  | format =
  | doi =
  | accessdate = 2007-06-07 }}</ref>

===Success of the action comedy genre: 1980s===
[[Image:Jcpmall.JPG|thumb|right|The film ''[[Police Story (film)|Police Story]]'', nicknamed "Glass Story" for its stunt work, is set in a modern period.]]
Jackie Chan made his first forays into the [[American film industry]] in the 1980s. His first Hollywood film was ''[[Battle Creek Brawl]]'' (or ''The Big Brawl''), directed by [[Robert Clouse]]. Chan then played a minor role in the 1981 film ''[[The Cannonball Run (film)|The Cannonball Run]]'', which grossed [[United States dollar|US$]]100 million worldwide. Despite being largely ignored by audiences in favour of established American actors like [[Burt Reynolds]], Chan was impressed by the [[outtakes]] shown at the [[closing credits]], inspiring him to include them in his future films.<ref name=FightingMaster/> After the commercial failure of ''[[The Protector (1985 film)|The Protector]]'' in 1985, Chan temporarily abandoned his attempts to break into the US market, returning his focus to [[Cinema of Hong Kong|Hong Kong films]].

